        "text": "In this lesson, you will learn a new way of looping over lists. Before we do that, let's revisit what we already know about loops.<div>Remember when we want to capitalize all words in this sentence:</div><div><br></div><div><pre><code>input = \"I love programming and Python is nice\"</code></pre><br>We first transformed the string into a list, with split:<br><br></div><div><pre><code>words = input.split()</code></pre><br>We created a new, empty list:<br><br></div><div><pre><code>output = []</code></pre></div><div><br>Then, for every word, we made it uppercase, and added it to the new list<br><pre><code>for w in words:<br>    uppercase_w = w.capitalize()    <br>    output.append(uppercase_w)</code></pre> <br></div><div>So, all in all, the loop part of the code is 4 lines long:</div><div><br></div><div><div><pre><code>output = []\nfor w in words:\n    uppercase_w = w.capitalize()    \n    output.append(uppercase_w)</code></pre></div><br>In the nest steps, we will learn a trick to do this in only 1 line of code!</div>",
